value.name: PLE intro - walkthrough
value.description: Hello, I’m really glad you’re here. I want you to know the fact that you picked up this app is a really big deal. You are important and your life is worth saving. After multiple suicide attempts myself and being in and out of hospitals for years, I can say I’ve been in really dark places myself. When I’m struggling, it’s like I have some kind of blinders on where the only way I can see to get me out of my pain is dying. I also want you to know, there is hope, even if you don’t believe it. My life is good today, it’s good because I put off dying and I learned to ask for help, and use skills to get better. This app will walk you through some activities to help right now, it will guide you through your stability plan and offer you tools and support that you can practice today and anytime you start to feel the need for help. Please hang in there and give this a try. I really want you to stay in this world long enough to get through how you’re feeling and realize just how much you matter.

category.name: Physical Coping Skill
category.why_text: Intense negative emotions can have a big impact on how we feel physically: our muscles tighten, our hearts race, and we might even feel sick to our stomach. These skills help change how you are feeling emotionally and physically. For example, using an exercise like Paced Breathing helps calm your mind and body so you can relax, feel calmer and more at ease.

value.message: I’m glad you’re trying this step by step guide. Let’s see what’s next.

category.name: Coping Distract
category.why_text: Managing intense negative emotions in the moment can be exhausting and really hard. Distraction is a powerful way to give yourself a break from your problems. They won't help you solve your problems, but they can help to take your mind off of them for a bit, giving you a chance to practice other skills.

category.name: Coping Senses
category.why_text: We can't always get away from the situation that is causing us distress as much as we might like to. We can, however, soothe our five senses (touch, smell, sight, hearing, and taste) to make the situation a little easier to stand. For eaxample; you can wear your comfy clothes, light a candle, watch a fire or listen to comforting music.

value.name: Reasons for Living - Walkthrough
value.description: Reasons for living are the most important things in your life that make you want to keep going even during the hardest moments: your family, pets, seeing tulips bloom, or the remake of your favorite film. For some, they’re easy to find. For others, finding even one can feel impossible and may require help and support to find one. When we do identify something, even if it seems small, it can help us get through the darkest of times as help to start building a life we want to live. Once you’ve identified your reasons for living, the key is to keep them near and in your mind during the difficult moments.

value: To eat real tacos in Mexico

value.name: Making Home Safer - Walkthrough
value.description: In moments of extreme distress, it's hard to think clearly. Emotions take over and the urge to die feels like the only way out. We know from people who have survived these feelings that the dark moments pass with time. The idea is that you find ways to get out the darkness and despair while also keeping yourself safe. This starts by giving yourself distance between you and the things you might use to harm or kill yourself. Having a plan is important. It might just be temporary, or one you use permanently. You get to decide. What matters is that you have a plan for yourself so if you find yourself wanting to die again, you are safe and have a chance to (re)build your life that you want to live. Making your home safe may be the single most important thing you can do to save your life.

category.name: Coping Courage
category.why_text: Making changes to improve our lives and move through our problems often takes a lot of courage. It helps to act opposite to how we feel in the moment. For example; If you want to run and hide, you would take a deep breath and take a step forward. If you feel small and powerless, you would can put your shoulders back, raise your head and look forward. The smallest acts of courage can have a powerful impact on how we feel in and about the moment.

category.name: Coping Help Others
category.why_text: Helping others when you're in a crisis can have a powerful effect on reducing your own distress. By focusing on others, your mind gets to take a break from your own problems. Studies show that helping others actually changes how people process emotions, helping them to feel happy and content.
